The WASP-139 Exoplanetary System


Overview

WASP-139 is a star with 0.92 times the mass of the Sun, and 0.8 times its radius. It is located 692.99 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 0.5 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

WASP-139 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the WASP-139 system


WASP-139 b

WASP-139 b was discovered by the SuperWASP-South observatory, in 2017-03, using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.06 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of WASP-139 b is 37.206 times the mass of Earth. The radius of WASP-139 b is 8.967 that of Earth. At more than 10 Earth masses, WASP-139 b is an ice giant, a planet that is made up mostly of volatiles like water, amonia and methane, and enveloped by a dense hydrogen and helium atmosphere, much like Uranus and Neptune in our solar system.
